<ns4356:section xmlns:ns4356="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.swing.developingSwingInterfaces.layoutManagersIntroduction">
    <ns4357:title xmlns:ns4357="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Introduction to Layout Managers</ns4357:title>
    <ns4358:para xmlns:ns4358="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">A container contains a collection of components and positions them within itself according
        to an algorithm supplied by a <ns4359:literal xmlns:ns4359="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">LayoutManager</ns4359:literal>. You can write your own
    layout manager which, for example, lays the components out on a circle. </ns4358:para>
    <ns4360:figure xmlns:ns4360="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns4361:title xmlns:ns4361="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Basic Layouts</ns4361:title>
    <mediaobject xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><imageobject><imagedata fileref="TestLayout.jpg"/></imageobject></mediaobject>
    </ns4360:figure>    
    <ns4362:para xmlns:ns4362="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java 2 supplies six standard layout managers. Four of the six layout managers are
        illustrated in figure above.
        To obtain a sophisticated user interface one usually nests containers within
        containers, each with their own layout manager. In this section we shall give a simple
        introduction to the layout managers and in the following sections where we discuss the
        various swing components we shall illustrate further features as well as how these layout
        managers are nested. </ns4362:para>
